social_posts.post_text: I was able to get my “Covid hair” cut and color chop chop from @ashayala_colorist_ in early November in #CarytownRVA. Thrilled with the results and having a healthy look similar to what I had pre-Madeleine and pre-2020 😂🥰 I went from accidental long sad hair (😬) to healthy, textured waves with damaged ends removed, with healthy hair cuticles feeling a lot better! Continued treatments, proper conditioning and masks - better absorbed with those bad ends gone and a nice color & gloss makes my hair feel like a new person and the postpartum thinning not as severe as before! Thank you Ashlee, as a friend and for my newfound confidence. 🥰💁🏻‍♀️

🎄#MerryChristmas as we make the most of our circumstances 🙃 M tested positive for C19 yesterday morning (Christmas Eve Eve). So we are staying here at home for Christmas for the first time & I know I’m being a big baby having never spent an Xmas in my 37 years away from my parents 🥹🎄❤️ Dad came over today to bring our gifts & stockings - we gave him their gifts including the ones Margaret picked out on her own at MNES. He also brought us a family favorite casserole, our share of some Christmas Dinner to cook here at home, & I’ve tried to find some #SelfCare time to cope. #MerryCrisis I’m testing negative as of now 🤞

“Benediction” in ‘Illuminated Calligraphy’
🖼️: my incredible aunt #GailCoppock

https://www.cafepress.com/gailsart/8089573

“The text of this ancient blessing is written in Old English script in sepia ink. Other media used are pigment inks, gold metallic ink and watercolor. The 9 7/8" x 6" original piece is on acid-free 140 lb. 100% rag d'Arches watercolor paper. The detailed designs, especially the knot work, were inspired by the "carpet" pages of the Book of Kells, an 8th century Irish illuminated manuscript created at the monastery on the island of Iona, then later moved to the monastery at Kells for safety from raiders.  It is now at @trinitycollegedublin , where I actually got to view it and other medieval manuscripts in person!” 
☘️

May is Celiac Disease Awareness Month and I thought it would be great to use my platform for educating and awareness of the importance of diagnosis and prevention with this serious autoimmune disorder.
👩🏻‍⚕️⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
FACT: Those with celiac disease have a 3.1x increased risk of death from liver disease, a 2.6x risk of death by pneumonia, and a 4x increased risk of small bowel cancer.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
🧑‍⚕️⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
FACT: The only treatment for celiac disease is lifelong adherence to a strict gluten-free diet. Ingesting small amounts of gluten, like crumbs from a cutting board or toaster, can trigger intestinal damage.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
👨‍🍳⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
FACT: If left untreated, celiac disease can lead to additional serious conditions like Type 1 diabetes, heart disease, infertility and miscarriage, epilepsy, and cancers.
🏩⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Learn more at celiac.org & @celiacdiseasefoundation 
.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

Sharing more about #CeliacDisease Awareness Month throughout May and hoping to educate my followers on the basics and more specific ways this autoimmune disorder impacts my life and my family’s life! Celiac disease is a genetic autoimmune disorder. If an immediate family member has celiac disease, then the risk is 1 in 10 that you will have it, too. Since my diagnosis in 2013, we now know that my second cousins have it, but my Dad recently tested negative for it (from that same side of the family). Studies show that 30-50% of people on a gluten-free diet continue to experience symptoms and have intestinal damage, confirming the need for adjunct treatments to the #glutenfree diet. 
👩🏻‍⚕️
Learn more at Celiac.org and from @celiacdiseasefoundation throughout this month.

For my birthday this year, I'm asking for donations to the Brister English Project (EIN: 920875602). I've chosen this nonprofit because Walter English’s mission means a lot to me, and I hope you'll consider contributing as a way to celebrate with me. Every little bit will help. Walt’s nonprofit helps American descendants of chattel slavery connect with their past through the expensive research of genealogy. Since he started in 2021, he has helped over 100 Black families directly at no cost to them. He also maintains and updates a database of collected free resources surrounding records on slavery and the reconstruction era and an incredibly active set of social media channels. He has big plans and an active GoFundMe even while experiencing his own medical health struggles. I admire Walt greatly.

There’s a tree on the main drive through the neighborhood that’s changing color, but only because someone hit it with their car a year ago… But it does finally go into the 60s at night time. The girls have been in school for already almost a month (first grade and pre-3s). I am adjusting to these changes and adapting my schedule accordingly. Working on continuing education for myself in our tech world with the social media to keep myself competitive and motivated. Putting in inquiries and sending out applications for jobs that truly motivate my heart and skills. Waiting for the air to turn crisp…

Cathy “La” LaDuke was posthumously inducted into the Virginia Independent Schools Athletic Association (VISAA) Hall of Fame dinner on Oct. 16 for her and three other inductees at the Hilton Short Pump in Richmond, Va.

‘Cathy LaDuke served at @chatham_hall for 34 years, including 20 years as @chathamhall_turtles athletic director from 1996 to 2015. She was instrumental in the founding of the Blue Ridge Conference (BRC), a predecessor of the Blue Ridge Athletic Conference (BRAC), where she served in a number of roles, including webmaster, treasurer, and vice president. During her time at Chatham Hall she coached a variety of sports, but was best known for her work in field hockey and lacrosse, and served many years on both sports’ VISAA committees.  LaDuke was selected by the @viaaa1995 as Athletic Director of the Year for Independent Schools in 2004, and was honored posthumously in 2021 with the VIAAA Distinguished Service Award.  She was proud of her VIAAA and NIAAA membership throughout her career.’

She devoted a majority of her life and career to the community of Chatham Hall, nurturing young women when they needed support and encouragement both in athletics and the arts. Her gift of photography helped many students find a new passion that they maybe could not find on the field. When she was not cheering them on the courts or in the ring, she encouraged them on the stage, at chapel, in their writings, wherever they found their passion. La was a babysitter for young faculty families who needed a break during the hectic pace of boarding school obligations, becoming the on campus Aunt for many young children raised on the sweeping acreage at Chatham Hall. Her smiling face was a delightful surprise when I would come across it in Lynchburg, Charlottesville or Lexington unexpectedly. It was always great to grab a quick hug, hello & visit for a while. Sitting on a field with my girls to watch CH field hockey coached by La was becoming a Fall tradition we enjoyed a great deal. To our family, including my parents, one of the main features of my success at Chatham Hall was the support of La. To us, Chatham Hall = the kind, encouraging memories and spirit of La.

Beautiful, smiling & busy @e_h20 
🥹 I will be sure to remember you in the most vibrant of ways (sometimes brunette and sometimes blonde). Teasing me for “did you really have to roll up on my campus tour like that?!” because I would yell by Fountain Plaza as she walked backwards with a full group of prospective students… occasionally between Fox Hall and @rmclib. Sometimes I’d yell “fore!” The commiserating in class, toiling the hours in the library studying for PSCI & elective classes, letting our hair down when campus jobs permitted it (& her early graduation didn’t make that easy either!). Embracing me as a returning older commuter student who wanted some friends without judgment and she was one of the first. I’ll always love her being part of that core “Macon Part II” phase of my life as I call it. I was hoping to get her down here for a stay at our beach house with @bossrva - a mini reunion of sorts. We 3 have text and social media message convos going back to school years… texting or messaging or both… pretty much everyday at many stretches. To have you ripped from us at 32 from cancer has been staggering. 
🩵
Your wishes from your friends were honored. I know you’re with Marley, you weren’t the same after that cute bean passed away. 
🐶 
In life, You Erica, were exceptional. You were so incredibly smart. RMC leadership respected you and it was fun seeing you in each edit for the alumni magazine, online article or a newsletter when I worked in the Marketing & Communications Office. In class the looks you would give classmates based on their responses were beyond epic. You had this one side eye that was crushingly serious and judgmental that I couldn’t ever forget it. Esp when I told you I was def no longer a Republican 😘🥹 The time Jessee got with you this year was special and important. Still smiling in that selfie. Who will I gossip about Royal Family drama, Bravo and early 2000s MTV pop culture nonsense with the added dash of legal sector jokes? 
💔
I’m never going to be the same after this loss in this season of our lives. I wish I could wrap you in a hug again. I love you, Erica.

🍁 Happy Thanksgiving 🍽 Love to everyone ☀️ @corollasunrise

He has sent me to bind up the brokenhearted,
 to proclaim freedom for the captives
  and release from darkness for the prisoners,
to proclaim the year of the Lord’s favor
  and the day of vengeance of our God,
to comfort all who mourn,
and provide for those who grieve —
to bestow on them a crown of beauty
  instead of ashes,
the oil of joy
  instead of mourning,
and a garment of praise
  instead of a spirit of despair.
They will be called oaks of righteousness,
 a planting of the Lord
  for the display of his splendor.
- Isaiah 61, NIV
🕯️ 🎄
Not a typical first Sunday in Advent verse. But my family has been going THROUGH IT. I needed this one today. It has been hard not to despair and question faith and beliefs in general (for those in family with that broader sense) with the pain of what has been going on between my health and the shocking sudden death of a family member for my cousins who were already grieving the loss of their Grandmother. It is a difficult season of life as we enter these holidays. We remember and remain grateful for the memories and support those who are here today. Those who are gone have left much wisdom, more than they realize 🥹

Whenever I get close to the #WinterSolstice, I think of this quote from #JohnSteinbeck, who wrote it in his 1962 travelogue “Travels with Charley: In Search of America.” (Charley was his poodle). Don’t take it too literal as a travelogue if you are reading it for the first time, by the way! Do you have #Yule, #Christmas, #Midwinter or Solstice traditions that give you a sweetness in these liminal twilight periods? I know these longer hours of darkness are hard on me, and always have been. I indulge in the habits of comfort and peace with loved ones, or stay at home if not feeling 100% healthy while enjoying books, warm beverages and favorite holiday meals. ​​​​​​​​
.​​​​​​​​
